column12: TOKENIZATION OF DISTRIBUTED COMPUTE RESOURCES
column13: The present invention provides systems and methods for tokenization of distributed compute resources. The distributed compute resources are provided in a multi-tenant hybrid fog computing cloud. The plurality of nodes are organized in a peer-to-peer edge network. The tokenization of distributed compute resources is automated and occurs in real time.

column12: Improvements relating to Mechanical Stokers.
column13: 4562. Cowan, J. March 4. Grates.-Relates to air seals for the backs of mechanical stokers of the chain-grate or similar type. The seal consists, as shown in Fig. 1, of one or more angle-plates b adjustably mounted upon a circular rod or tubular bearer c and held in position by lugs d. The rear edge of the plate b is as close as practicable to the fire-bridge h, with which it makes an air seal, while the front edge, preferably formed with renewable noses k of cast iron, in its normal position is slightly above the grate. The air seal is adjusted by rods m, s and levers o, t, the rod m being pivoted to the rear of the plate b. In its normal position, the front edge of the plate b is sealed by the ashes upon the grate. In the event of ash of a slightly larger size than the opening between the nose k and the grate striking against the front edge of the air seal, the latter turns about the pivots at the rear and rises off the bearing c, an opening being formed large enough for the ash to pass. If a considerable amount of large ashes accumulates in front of the nose k, the plate b may be tilted, as shown, to allow it to pass.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements in Water Tube Boilers.
column13: 16,436. Cowan, J. Aug. 15. Water-tube boilers priming, preventing. - To increase the dryness of steam taken from boilers having two or more steam drums, the connecting- tubes between the drums are so arranged in combination with deflecting-plates and partitions that the steam is all conducted into one drum, preferably the feed-supply drum, where the ebullition is less violent, and taken thence to a division or pocket in another drum to which the stop valve is attached. Fig. 1 shows the invention applied to a boiler of the kind described in Specification No. 9924, A.D. 1901. The middle part of the centre drum b is divided off by a partition w to form a space from which the steam is finally taken, and into which some of the connecting-tubes open, the remainder of these tubes simply connecting the main space of the drum b with the feed-supply drum c. The steam generated in the drums a and b is led through the connecting-tubes to the drum c, and thence to the space above the partition w. Baffles such as 2 and 3 protect the entrances to the connecting-tubes. Fig. 8 shows a modified arrangement applied to a different form of boiler. In this case, the connecting-tubes are in two sets in different planes, and the steam from the drums a, b first passes into the drum c, whence the whole of the steam generated passes first to a space 11 at the top of the drum b and finally to a space 8 at the top of the drum a, to which the stop valve is connected. Baffle-plates are fitted as before. The application to double-ended marine boilers is illustrated in the Specification.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements in and relating to Mechanical Stokers.
column13: 694. Cowan, J. Jan. 9. Grates.-In connection with chain-grate mechanical stokers, a subsidiary movable grate is provided under the inner end of the main chain grate, in order to prevent excess of air from being admitted at this point and to ensure the complete combustion of the fuel deposited on it with the ash from the main grate. Fig. 1 shows a tilting subsidiary grate a, which may be fixed in any position or left free to tilt by the weight of the accumulated ash. Modified arrangements of tilting- grates are described and illustrated, these grates being pivoted in the centre, and, in some cases, automatically and continuously rocked by connection with the stoker mechanism. Fig. 4 shows a subsidiary chain-grate s, and Fig. 5 a subsidiary grate in the form of a perforated rotating drum t mounted in bearings which yield laterally to allow the passage of lumps of clinker between the drum and the firebridge wall.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements in Boiler Furnaces.
column13: 7178. Cowan, J. April 5. Steam-generator furnaces.-A boiler is provided with two furnaces, one at each end, one being constructed to burn megasse or coal dust, and the other ordinary coal, and either being capable of being used at will while the other is rendered inoperative. Fig. 1 shows one arrangement, adapted to a boiler of the "Stirling" type. At one end is an ordinary coal-burning furnace l, and at the other a megasse-burning furnace m with a feeding- shoot t and an incline s down which the megasse slides to the grate p. A depending bridge v causes air entering with the megasse to be directed downwards towards the grate. The flame passes over the bridge i into the combustion chamber n under the boiler, and then rises into the tube space in front of the coal-burning furnace. Suitable doors are provided for closing the air and fuel openings of either furnace. Wood fuel may be inserted at y. Fig. 5 shows a modified arrangement with a coal-burning furnace having an inclined grate 3 and a lower horizontal grate 5. Coal is fed through a shoot 4 which may have a steam-jet blower. A door 7 gives access for cleaning the grate. Fig. 6 shows an arrangement for burning either coal dust or ordinary coal. The coal-dust burner is placed behind the boiler at 18, and the fire bars 13 and ashtray 15 of the coal-burning furnace are removable, the latter being used to cut off the coal-dust burner when required. A coal-burning furnace of the kind shown in Fig. 5 may be used in the combination shown in Fig. 6.

column12: An Apparatus for Filling Bladders with Lard and the like
column13: 4399. Cowan, J. Feb. 22. Bottling.-Relates to apparatus for filling bladders with lard &c. The neck of the bladder is put over a nozzle f, and is held by clamping-jaws d, which are actuated against the action of springs c<1> by a cam-ring b. This ring engages the upper ends of levers c which carry the jaws d, and is provided with a handle b<1>. To deliver the lard &c., the piston or valve a is raised by its handle a<1>. column12: Improvements in Steam Boiler Feed Water Purifiers and Heaters.
column13: 17,327. Cowan, J. Sept. 29. Feedwater, heating and purifying.- The water is caused to travel in thin films over a series of trays, falling from one to the other, and being exposed to the action of live or exhaust t steam. The water enters the apparatus through the valve v and rises in the central tube g. Being deflected by the bell x, it flows outwards over the tray k, and overflows on to the next tray p. Flowing inwards over this tray, it falls through a central aperture to the next tray below, and so on. Having reached the bottom of the containing- vessel, it rises through a straining-plate o into the chamber n, whence it escapes through the tube e, surrounding the tube g, to the outlet z. Steam is admitted at w. A reagent may be supplied with the water if desired. Deposited impurities may be blown out at 4. The trays are held together and suspended from the cover by bolts t and distance-pieces u. The lower trays are preferably fitted with short tubes 2 to allow the steam to circulate freely. The bracket y is for the attachment of lifting apparatus for removing the cover and trays.

column12: Apparatus for Raising or Lowering and Turning Hot Steel Slabs in Cogging or Rolling Mills.
column13: 5362. Cowan, J. March 10. Rolling; shearing.-Hot steel slabs, which have been rolled from blooms in cogging or rolling mills and run on live rolls to the shearing-machine for trimming the ends, instead of being passed through the shearing-machine to cut the opposite ends and thus overheating the blades, are run back after shearing one end, and are then raised and turned round to present the opposite end to the cutters. This is effected by a table B, which is mounted, normally below the rollers C, on an hydraulic or other power ram A, which has inclined grooves D and vertical grooves d at the connecting points engaging screws E in the cylinder A<1>. After turning, the ram is lowered, and the slab is then fed forwards by the rolls to the cutters.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements in Water Tube Boilers
column13: 9924. Cowan, J. May 13. Water-tube boilers.-In place of the two lower water drums usually employed in boilers of the Stirling type, a single divided drum d is provided ; in a double-ended marine boiler, however, there may be two divided lower drums, one for each end. The drum d is divided by a partition A provided with openings. The feed-drum c is also divided, by a partial partition n, so that the feedwater does not pass into circulation until it has entered the rear division of the drum d, in which most of the pre cipitated impurities are deposited. The front portion of the feed-drum is connected as shown to the steam drums a, b, so that any accumulation of water in these drums, owing to the forcing of the boiler, can escape into the feed-drum and over the partition n. In a double-ended boiler with a single lower drum, the latter has two partitions, as also has the feed-drums.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements relating to Separately Fired Superheaters.
column13: 4653. Cowan, J. March 6. Superheaters, steam; water-tube boilers; watercirculation, promoting.-Consists of an independently-fired steam superheater which with its protecting-screen of steam-generating tubes appears exteriorly as a five-drum type of Stirling boiler. Steam from a battery of boilers enters the upper drum a, and, after passing to the lower drum c and to the upper drum b through banks of tubes d, e, escapes by the outlet n. The protecting steam generator consists of the tubes g which connect the drums i, h. The steam generated passes by the pipe k to the superheating-drum a. To ensure a downward circulation of the water, tubes of the series g are embedded in the furnace settings. A valve-controlled pipe s connects the drum c with the water space of the drum h so that the superheater may be flooded when desired. The flap valve o situated in the steam pipe m is connected to the furnace damper p in order that the steam entering the superheater may control the position of the damper. In some cases, the single lower steam drum of the superheater may be replaced by two drums in direct communication with each other, a branch of superheating-tubes being connected to each of these drums.
column15: COWAN JOHN

column12: Improvements in and relating to Steam Superheaters, Feed Water Heaters and the like.
column13: 1494. Cowan, J. Jan. 22. Superheaters, steam; feedwater, heating.-A which of straight tubes is secured in tube-plates which are covered by end chambers as shown in Fig. 1, the joints between the tubes and the plates being within the chambers. The tubes are arranged across the path of the furnace gases, and the end chambers are free to move to allow expansion and contraction of the tubes. A space is left among the tubes as shown in Fig. 3. A semicircular shield h is fitted round the tubes, so that it may be moved to protect them from the furnace gases when not in use. Fig. 5 shows such a superheater or feedwater-heater in connection with a " Stirling " boiler. A damper n acts to cause the gases to pass among the tubes, or, when in the position shown in dotted lines, allows them to pass free of the tubes. To allow the damper to be operated simultaneously with the shield h, the latter has a projecting strip r with fingers or tappets q and s, which, when the shield is turned, come in contact with the damper. A separate damper may, however, be employed, with or without the shield.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Water Tube Boilers
column13: 4277. Cowan, J. March 1. Water-tube boilers.-A boiler of the Stirling type, as shown in Fig. 1, is formed with its lower rear drum superposed upon the wall k so that it overhangs the grate. By this means, the length of the boiler at the stoking-level is reduced without a diminition in the boiler efficiency. Where two lower water drums are used, the front drum only is raised and brought over the grate. Partition plates n, o, as described in Specification No. 3762, A.D. 1903, are fitted to the drum to form a quiescent space at the back where feed from the upper drum enters. The plates are preferably hinged or portable. The upper front' steam and water drum a in this type of boiler is made to overhang the fire-doors and furnace front, whereby an increased stoking space is obtained.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Registering Appliances for Measuring-taps.
column13: 19,995. Cowan, J. Sept. 7. Counting-apparatus; measured quantities, delivering. - Measuring-taps of the kind described in Specification No. 1793, A.D. 1885, and known as "Ross " taps are provided with mechanism for registering the total amount of liquor drawn off. At each delivery of liquor the handle 11 of the tap, and with it a rack 12 secured thereto, is withdrawn and oscillates, through a pinion 10, a lever 13 pivoted at 22 to the casing 1. The lever 13 carries a pawl 15 engaging a ratchet-wheel 16, on the spindle of which is a pointer moving over a scale. A counting-train 4 carrying other pointers for indicating the higher units of volumes is geared to the spindle of the wheel 16. In a modification, in which the casing 1 is disposed sideways with respect to the barrel 2 of the tap, the pinion 10 is dispensed with and the rack 12, which need only have one tooth, engages directly with the lever 13. Specification No. 25,028, A.D. 1896, is referred to.

column12: Improved Means for Cooling the Grips of Charging Machines used in connection with Heating-furnaces for Iron and Steel
column13: 18,761. Cowan, J. Aug. 22. Charging and discharging. - For cooling the grips of charging-machines used for placing steel slabs in and removing them from heating-furnaces, water under pressure is sprayed over them from perforated pipes arranged as shown in elevation in Fig. 3. The pipes are arranged in a recess C<1> in the floor, the base of the recess being perforated to drain off the water. Water which enters the pipe A passes to a central pipe or pipes D, which are perforated on the upper surface to spray water upwards, and to branches D', D' connected to U-shaped swivelling pipes E, E<1> which may be swung so as to lie in the recess C<1>, or vertically so as to envelop or extend over or around the grips to be cooled. A cock (not shown) is provided on the pipe A to regulate the supply of water.

column12: Method and apparatus for testing wear, size and residual stress conditions
column13: Wheel testing apparatus according to the invention comprises at least one search unit positioned "in-track" replacing a portion of a rail so that the gauged wheels of a passing railroad train roll thereover. Each search unit has a thin vertical rail aligned with the gauge edge of the track for supporting each passing wheel adjacent to its flange, and thereby exposing the running surface of the wheel for testing in a zone which does not interfere with the wheel's path. Each search unit has two ultrasonic transducers enclosed in a flexible fluid-filled boot and are positioned adjacent to the thin vertical rail in the test zone under the running surfaces of passing wheels, the fluid-filled boot providing good ultrasonic coupling therewith. The transducers are angled and opposed to send ultrasonic pulses around the wheel in opposite directions. Echoes indicate defects and through transmission times indicate wheel size and wear. Failure of the wheel to accept any significant amount of energy indicates high residual stress.
column15: COWAN JOHN VINCENT;;COWAN GERALD DE G;;COWAN JOHN GERALD

column12: Method and implant device for grafting adjacent vertebral bodies
column13: A methodology for grafting together adjacent bony structures is provided using an implant device having an endplate with an inner disc portion and outer ring portion spaced from the inner disc portion by a connecting wall disposed there between. An endplate interior surface includes a retaining structure for securing the endplate to one of the bony structures, and endplate an exterior surface has an integrally formed socket. A ball-joint rod has a longitudinally extending body and an end, and at least a portion of the ball-joint rod end is curvilinear in shape. The curvilinear ball-joint rod end is rotatably disposed in the endplate socket to fixedly interconnect the bony structures.
column15: COWAN JOHN A

column12: VERTEBRAL IMPLANT
column13: An implant and method for attaching to vertebral members with the implant including a plate and a cage. The plate is configured to be positioned against and anchored to the bodies of the vertebral members. The plate may also extend into the intervertebral space between the vertebral members. The cage extends outward from the plate and is positioned within the intervertebral space. The implant provides a low profile that is positionable between the bodies of the vertebral members and the lamina/pars/facet joint. The implant may be implanted utilizing a lateral access to the spine. The implant and method may further include just the plate without the cage.

column12: DISPLAY FOR MULTI-CHANNEL SONARS
column13: This invention discloses an improved visual display arrangement incorporated in and uniquely combined with a multi-channel sonar system. Improved sweep drive using electromagnetic deflection and an improved magnetic focusing arrangement contribute to the operation thereof. A direct coupled video amplifier and a regulated high voltage power supply complete the novel display arrangement.

column13: A trophy assembly comprises a base 30 and at least one decorative element 46. column13: A computer implemented method for facilitating in-person activities includes the steps of electronically receiving information from a user for a proposed in-person activity, electronically generating a tentative activity posting for the proposed in-person activity within a group feed, electronically receiving positive interest level for the tentative activity posting from users of the group feed, electronically generating an activity page for the proposed in-person activity when a predetermined number of the positive interest level is received from the users, and electronically deleting the tentative activity posting for the proposed in-person activity at a predetermined time if the predetermined number of the positive interest level has not been received from the users. The activity page for the proposed in-person activity permits users to electronically enroll in the proposed in-person activity.

column13: A continuous tone image A is used to expose photoresist C through support B and developed to produce a resist of different depths. column12: Method for engraving three dimensional images
column13: A simplified method for producing a smoothly graduated, three dimensional engraving in a substrate using a shotblast resist. The method includes preparing a continuous tone transparency having various levels of tone which correspond to the varying levels of depth required in desired image to be engraved into the substrate. A resist film is then contact exposed through its film base and through the continuous tone transparency of the image to an actinic source of electromagnetic radiation for a specific quantity of exposure and the varying levels of radiation transmission through the various tones of the transparency result in a controlled differential exposure of the resist film. This correspondingly results in progressive hardening and toughening through the resist film from its film base according to the various levels of actinic radiation to which it is exposed. The unhardened areas are then washed out and a resist having a smoothly varying thickness is thus produced. The resist is then bonded to the substrate and shotblasted. As the shotblasting process proceeds, the thinner areas of the resist are progressively worn away, exposing more and more of the substrate to the action of the shot and thus automatically producing a controlled and smoothly graduated three dimensional cut into the substrate.

Feedwater, heating and purifying. -Feedwater is heated, purified, and stored till required in cylinders resembling that described in Specification No. 17,327, A.D. 1900. They may be connected up to serve one or more of a series of boilers. Thechamber a, Fig. 1, placed above the level of the boiler receives the feedwater through the central pipe f from the piped. Live steam is admitted at the inlet k to heat it as it passes over the trays b. The lower space c serves for the storage of the water, which is purified by the heat of the steam and, in some cases, by the addition of soda. The precipitated salts can be withdrawn through the pipe m and the purified water by the pipe hand valve j to the boiler when desired. As illustrated in Fig. 2, several such cylinders a<1>, a<2>, a<3>, a<4> may be connected singly or collectively to several boilers, suitable pipes with cocks being provided.

column12: Improvements in and relating to the Generation of Steam.
column13: 3 5 3 0. Cowan, J., and Fuller, A. J. Feb. 13. Thermal storage apparatus. -A superheater is fitted in connexion with thermal storage vessels in steamgenerating plant. Superheated steam is thus supplied to the storage vessels in place of saturated steam. The invention is described in connexion with Stirling boilers. The outlet k of the superheater e, which may have two or more passes for the steam, is connected by a pipe n with the storage vessels a and by another pipe q with the main steam-pipe s. The pipe q has a branch t communicating with the middle steam and water drum through a stop valve u. By means of this branch, saturated steam may mix with the superheated steam. The temperature of the latter may also be regulated by a butterfly valve f, forming the usual partition in the upper drum of the superheater. The storage vessels are fitted with internal baffles such as are described in Specification No. 18,350, A.D. 1904.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Plant for the Generation of Steam
column13: 5759. Cowan, J., and Baillie, R. March 9. Feed - water, heating ; superheaters, steam. - Installations for generating steam are fitted with a feed-heater and a superheater, the feed-heater being worked at a pressure greater than that in the boilers ; the steam generated in the feed-heater is passed into the superheater with the steam from the boilers. The Figure shows a feed-heater and a superheater arranged in the form of a five-drum Stirling boiler. The feed - heater, formed by the upper drum a, tubes c, and lower drum b, is arranged as a screen to the superheater, which is formed by the remaining tubes and drums. The feed is supplied to the lower drum b from an elevated hotwell or tank l by an injector m, which is worked by steam from the drum a or by superheated steam. In some cases, the drum a may be divided into two compartments and the feed-water introduced to one of them. A pipe j connects the steam space of the drum a with the rear drum e of the superheater ; a reducing-valve may be fitted in this pipe. The pipe leading from the boilers is shown at k. The hot water is supplied automatically to the boilers by the difference of pressure, the delivery being controlled by floats in the usual manner. If desired, the feedheater may be worked at the same pressure as the boiler but placed at a higher level. Flooding- connexions are provided to enable the whole apparatus to work as a boiler in the ordinary way.

column13: 5747. Cowan, J., and Jones, L. March 9. Water-tube boilers; superheaters, s t e a m.- Superheaters for Stirling and other boilers are arranged away from the main path of the furnace gases. In Fig. 1, a superh e a t e r , consisting of upper and lower drums h, i with tubes z connecting them, is shown located in a pocket b in the front end of the boiler and screened by a wall of water tubes c. These tubes are connected above to the drum d and below to an auxiliary drum e, which communicates by two large pipes g with the main water drum d<1>. For regulating the temperature in the chamber b, cold feed, or more or less hot water from the feed heater, is supplied to the tubes c through connections T in the pipes g. A portion of the furnace gases pass through the water wall c into the lower end of the chamber b, and thence to the upper end, where they escape amongst the generating tubes a, or are lead through a bye-pass s to the back end of the boiler, or to the feed heater. The bye-pass, shown separately in Fig. 2, consists of a perforated metal box divided in halves, which extend across the front of the boiler, each half being secured to the access doors r. A steam jet 10 is fitted in the end chamber u of the box. The drums h, i may be fitted with partitions dividing the tubes into groups in series ; or they may be replaced by divided headers, shown separately in Figs. 7 and 8, and provided with a separate cover for each compartment. Fig. 4 shows a modification in which the screen of water tubes is dispensed with, the superheater being arranged above a firebrick arch x overhanging the fire-door.

column12: Method of making camshaft lobes
column13: Sharp edges formed during forging are removed from cam lobes by tumbling prior to machining of mounting bores which have been rough formed by punching. column12: THROTTLE POSITION SENSOR ASSEMBLY
column13: Throttle body assemblies having improved throttle position sensing assemblies and a method of integrating a throttle position sensor assembly with a throttle body assembly are described. The method comprises the steps of: i) press-fitting a sensor element onto a shaft of a throttle plate of a throttle body assembly; ii) engaging one or more inwardly extending members of the sensor element with one or more recessed portions formed on the shaft of the throttle plate; and iii) disposing an inductive rotary position sensor proximate the sensor element, wherein the press-fit engagement and one or more inwardly extending members limit axial and rotational movement of the sensor element with respect to the throttle plate, and wherein the inductive rotary position sensor detects a relative position of the sensor element for the purpose of ascertaining a position of the throttle plate.

column12: Systems and methods for locating microserver nodes in proximity to edge devices using georouting
column13: Systems and methods for locating microserver nodes in proximity to edge devices using georouting. Microservers automatically form a global peer-to-peer network to serve edge functions and content to edge devices. Edge devices use HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP) to execute serverless functions or otherwise retrieve data from edge nodes and/or microservers located in proximity to the HTTP client. The cloud platform locates the nearest edge node and/or microserver. Edge devices georoute HTTP requests to the nearest edge node and/or microserver. Serverless functions are implemented in secure, isolated environments using a blockchain.

column12: Means for limiting to a predetermined value the road speed of a vehicle
column13: 1,040,447. Regulating I.C. engines. ROVER CO. Ltd., and ISO-SPEEDIC CO. Ltd. Sept. 17, 1963 [Sept. 20, 1962], No. 35784/62. Heading FIB. [Also in Division B7] In a motor vehicle driven by an I.C. engine through change speed gearing and including a governor adjustable to limit engine speed to any desired value in a predetermined range, a road speed limiting device effective only in the higher ratios comprises stop means which operate when such ratios are selected to prevent the engine speed exceeding that appropriate to the desired maximum road speed in that ratio. Selection of third or fourth gear closes one of switches 10, 12 to energize one of solenoids 11, 13 which displace levers, 17, 18 carrying stops 27, 28 for co-operation with a lever 23 to limit movement in the increased speed direction of a governor control rod 26. The lever 23 carries a follower 30 maintained by a spring 31 in contact with a lever 22 connected by a rod 29 to the accelerator pedal whereby the governor control rod 26 follows the whole range of accelerator movement in the low ratios. The switches 10, 12 are connected to the vehicle battery either directly or through the ignition switch 14. Springs 20, 21 support the levers 17, 18 and the attached solenoid armatures 15, 16 when the solenoids are not energized. In another arrangement (Fig. 6, not shown) the extent to which a throttle control (or fuel metering valve in the case of a fuel-injection engine) can follow under spring bias the movements of the accelerator pedal is limited by a stop positioned by the governor, and movement in the increased speed direction of the governor control lever is limited in high ratios by solenoid actuated stops. In a further arrangement, Fig. 7 (not shown), the solenoids position stops which control the ratio of a lever connection between the accelerator and the governor so that when the accelerator is fully depressed in the high ratios the governor setting corresponds to the desired maximum road speed. The solenoids and switches may be replaced by mechanical, pneumatic or hydraulic means for positioning the stops.

column12: Reactor device
column13: The invention relates to a reactor device (1), comprising: at least one vessel (100) having a first end section (101) and an opposing second end section (102), wherein the two end sections (101, 102) each delimit an opening (O, O') of the at least one vessel (100), so that a fluid medium (F) can enter the at least one vessel (100) through one of the openings (O), flow through the at least one vessel (100), and leave the at least one vessel (100) through the other opening (O'), and a first manifold (200) comprising a first recess (201) and a first aperture (202), wherein the first end section (101) of the at least one vessel (100) is designed to be arranged in said first recess (201) in an operating position of the first manifold (200), so that the opening (O) delimited by the first end section (101) of the vessel (100) is in fluid communication with said first aperture (202) and fluid medium (F) can be discharged into the vessel (100) or can be drawn off the vessel (100) through said first aperture (202) of the first manifold (200). According to the invention, the reactor device (1) comprises a first seal (10) for sealing a gap between the first end section (101) of the at least one vessel (100) and a circumferential inner side (201 a) of the first recess (201) in the operating position of the first manifold (200), wherein the first seal (10) encompasses the first end section (101) of the at least one vessel (100) and rests with an outer side (10a) against said inner side (201 a) of the first recess (201) of the first manifold (200).

column12: User-Controlled Application Access to Resources
column13: A host application on a computing device displays an icon or other visual representation of a resource of the computing device, and receives a request from one of one or more applications hosted by the host application. The request is a request to access the resource represented by the icon or other visual representation of the resource, and in response to the request the appearance of the icon or other visual representation of the resource is altered. The requesting application is allowed to access the resource only if a user selection of the displayed icon or other visual representation is received.

column12: Motorized amusement ride apparatus and method
column13: A self-propelled amusement ride apparatus has a base with a frame mounted on wheels. A motor is coupled to the wheels for transmitting power thereto for moving the apparatus over a non-tracked support surface. A riding body is coupled to the base and has a seating surface for supporting a rider. The body is shaped to resemble an animal, character, vehicle, vessel, aircraft, architectural structure or other recognizable object selected to provide an amusing or entertaining appearance. A controller of the apparatus is positioned for operation by the rider while being supported on the seating surface for controlling speed and direction of movement of the apparatus. A human rider may be moved over a support surface by actuating the amusement ride apparatus. The rider directs the movement of the apparatus over a non-tracked support surface using the controller.

column12: Throttle position sensor assembly
column13: Throttle body assemblies having improved throttle position sensing assemblies and a method of integrating a throttle position sensor assembly with a throttle body assembly are described. The method comprises the steps of: i) press-fitting a sensor element onto a shaft of a throttle plate of a throttle body assembly; ii) engaging one or more inwardly extending members of the sensor element with one or more recessed portions formed on the shaft of the throttle plate; and iii) disposing an inductive rotary position sensor proximate the sensor element, wherein the press-fit engagement and one or more inwardly extending members limit axial and rotational movement of the sensor element with respect to the throttle plate, and wherein the inductive rotary position sensor detects a relative position of the sensor element for the purpose of ascertaining a position of the throttle plate.

column12: Customer impact predictive model and combinatorial analysis
column13: Systems and methods for objective Deployment Failure risk assessments are provided, which may include fault trees. Systems and methods for the analysis of fault trees are provided as well. The risk assessments system may involve the development of a fault tree, assigning initial values and weights to the events within that fault tree, and the subsequent revision of those values and weights in an iterative fashion, including comparison to historical data. The systems for analysis may involve the assignment of well-ordered values to some events in a fault tree, and then the combination those values through the application of specialized, defined gates. The system may further involve the revision of specific gates by comparison to historical or empirical data.

Flooring-blocks; moulds. -Fire-proof flooring is formed of hollow trapezium-shaped c o ncrete blocks, recessed at the ends to rest on the joists, and strengthened with inclined webs e, f which meet at the centre ; concrete k is filled in between the joists and blocks. The lower flanges of the joists are protected by slabs n, and air-ducts g, p form continuous air passages throughout the structure. The blocks may be reinforced by bars q, s. According to the Provisional Specification, the blocks may be formed in frames composed of wooden blocks which carry pins for the air-ducts and supports for the reinforcing-bars, some of the wooden blocks being wedge-shaped and the whole being surrounded by an outer case. When the outer case is removed and the wedge-shaped blocks are knocked out, the remainder may be easily removed.

column12: Swab dispenser
column13: A swab dispenser system is provided that includes a reusable outer receptacle and a replaceable refill container insertable therewithin. The outer receptacle is formed with a fin projecting vertically upwardly and centrally positioned on the bottom panel of the receptacle. The fin has a horizontal length greater than a width thereof. The refill container on its bottom wall also includes a fin. The fin of the refill container has a hollow interior for form-fittingly receiving the fin projecting upwardly from the receptacle bottom panel. Function of the fin is to allow a consumer to properly orient the refill container when placing same into the receptacle. The fin also functions to direct swabs into a proper arrangement when they are being factory filled into the container. Furthermore, the position and geometry of the fin maximizes the number of swabs fillable into the container.

column12: Adjustable shock absorber
column13: A shock absorber, in an exemplary embodiment, especially suited for motorcycles and the like characterized as being fabricated of a minimum number of components assembled in a manner which permits rebuilding of worn components and wherein selected variable dampening is obtained through the provision of external adjustment device for varying the degree of dampening. The adjustability features allow for variable jounce and rebound factors to accommodate both normal and severe driving conditions and to permit compensation thereof, all without dismantling or demounting of the shock absorber from the vehicle with which it is associated. Adjustment in one instance comprises metering the hydraulic fluid and in the other instance varying the disposition of the main compression spring. Structure on the body of the shock absorber is provided to dissipate heat thereby increasing the quality of performance of the shock absorber during jounce and rebound conditions. Also disclosed is a piston having novel orifice and valve arrangement through which hydraulic fluid flows. In other embodiments a compensator device within the cylinder of the shock absorber prevents aeration and hence breakdown of the hydraulic fluid. Other unique features are also disclosed.

column12: Improvements relating to electrical apparatus
column13: 1,138,712. Phototypesetting apparatus; cathode-ray tube circuits. ELLIOTT BROTHERS (LONDON) Ltd. 13 Jan., 1967 [21 Jan., 1966], No. 2788/66. Headings H4F and H4T. Phototypesetting apparatus comprises four flash tubes 3, Fig. 1 (only two shown), one of which is energized in response to a signal from a digital computer 1 via a buffer store 2 and a switch unit 4 to project opaque characters carried on the mask 15 associated with the energized tube on to the screen of a vidicon camera tube 6. Each character carried by the mask is associated with an opaque base line 17, Fig. 3, parallel to and a fixed distance below a type reference line 18, and of length related to the width of the character. Vidicon 6 scans normal to the base lines 17 the part only of the screen 13 carrying the charge pattern of the character required and its base line (e.g. as with "h" in Fig. 3). The output signal of the vidicon is transmitted to a cathode ray tube 9. The video and raster inputs to the cathode and scan coils 11 of the CRT 9 representing the character (e.g. as with "y" of Fig. 3) are started when the pulse, occurring as the vidicon scan beam crosses the base line 17 on each line of the vidicon raster, reaches the driving amplifier 10, thereby providing an accurate vertical and horizontal positioned register of the character in relation to the start of each scan line forming the input raster. The characters appearing in screen 19 are projected on to a film 21, the characters being accurately positioned by means of a positioning mirror assembly including a mirror 25, Fig. 4, a transparent scale 26, a light sensitive cell 27 and a housing 28. The beam of the CRT 9 is controlled to fall within the portion 24 of the screen 19 so that its image falls after reflection by mirror 25 on to the parallel lines 29, Fig. 5, of scale 26. The beam of the CRT is then deflected in a direction normal to the parallel lines 29 and as the image crosses each of the lines 29 a pulse is produced by cell 27. These pulses are fed to a beam registration circuit (not shown) which is responsive to an output (not shown) of the buffer store to control the scan coils 11 of the CRT to accurately position (horizontally) the image in relation to film 21. The beam is then moved so that the image on scale 26 moves in a direction normal to and toward the base line 30 of scale 26, and as the image reaches the scale base line 30 a pulse is produced to cell 27 which is used to accurately position the image vertically in relation to film 21. Resulting from the accurate horizontal and vertical registration of the beam, the character raster (the start of each line of which is coincident with the position of base line 17) on the screen 19 is formed in portion 23 to produce an accurately positioned image on film 21, the start of each line coinciding with the base line 30 of scale 26. Film 21 remains stationary during the composition of each line of print and is moved only to start a new line. The size of the characters projected to the film may be magnified electronically, and if a single character size on mask 15 is used to produce a number of character sizes on film 21 it is desirable in order to maintain correct positioning of the characters in the film to provide a number of base lines 17 under each character. Alternatively a single base line 17 may be used in conjunction with a scale 26 having a number of base lines 30 each associated with a different degree of magnification.

column12: SYRINGES, SYRINGE INTERFACES AND SYRINGE PLUNGERS FOR USE WITH MEDICAL INJECTORS
column13: A syringe includes a body and a plunger movably disposed within the body. The plunger includes a wall having an inner surface and one or more inwardly projecting flanges disposed on the inner surface of the wall. Preferably, the inner surface of the wall defines a retaining shoulder formed along an axial plane thereof and the inwardly projecting flanges are radially spaced along the interior surface of the wall and extend in a longitudinal direction proximal to the retaining shoulder. The syringe may be used with an injector including a drive member. The drive member preferably includes at least one retaining member adapted to engage the retaining shoulder of the syringe plunger to allow the drive member to retract the plunger with the body of the syringe. Further, the drive member preferably includes one or more outwardly extending flange members adapted to be engaged by the inwardly projecting flanges of the syringe plungers. The outwardly extending flange members are operably linked to the at least one retaining member such that, when the syringe body is rotated and the inwardly projecting flanges on the plunger engage and move the outwardly extending flange members on the drive member, the at least one retaining member on the drive member is retracted and disengaged from the retaining shoulder of the syringe plunger.

Powered rollers may be embedded into the forks of a pallet-lift mechanism and on top of the vehicle body. An exemplary embodiment may be fully autonomous. Hinged sliding windows; sash-cord attachments. -The sash-cord attachment for hinged sliding window sashes comprises a sliding plate C, to which the cord is attached and on which is mounted a sliding bolt F with a rotatable sleeve D, and a fitting E fixed on the sash and having a projection E<1> engaging a slot D' in the sleeve D. When the sash is turned into the room, the bolt F is shot into a retaining-plate on the frame and, at the same time, the sleeve D is rotated under the action of a pin D' which engages a curved slot C' in the plate C, so that the projection E<1> clears the slot in the sleeve. The hinge consists of a pin carried by a part M, which is provided with a projection N working in a helical slot in a casing secured on the sash so that, when turned up out of use, it recedes into a recess L in the casing, and, when turned down, it projects ready for engagement with socket plates on the frame.

column12: DYNAMIC SOUND SCATTERING
column13: This thesis presents the results of three main experimental projects; a stud y of ultrasonic wave propagation in strongly scattering materials, the use of the results of this first study to develop new techniques in ultrasonic correlation spectroscopy , and the use of these techniques to measure the dynamics of particles in fluidized beds. The first project involves the investigation of wave propagation in random, inhomogeneous materials that scatter ultrasound strongly (i.e. materials where the scattering mean free path is comparable to the ultrasonic wavelength .lambda.). I have measured t he velocities of the weak ballistic pulse that travels through these materials without scattering out of the forward direction. In the intermediate frequency regime, where .lambda. ~ th e size of the scatterer, these measurements reveal strong dispersion in the ballistic mode s, caused by both resonant scattering in the material and tortuosity effects. The dependence of the dispersion on the volume fraction of scatterers is investigated; very good agreement between the ballistic velocities and an effective medium theory, based on a spectral function approach, is found at all volume fractions. The diffusion approximation for the scattered waves is tested by measuring the ensemble-averaged transmitted intensityin pulsed ultrasonic experiments. The volume fraction dependence of the wave diffusion coefficient and the absorption time is investigated experimentally, and parameters that govern diffusive propagation are modeled using an extension of the spectral function approach. Using the results of this wave propagation study, we have developed two new ultrasonic spectroscopy techniques. Dynamic Sound Scattering (DSS) uses sing ly scattered sound to measure the rms velocity of scatterers. Diffusing Acousti c Wave Spectroscopy (DAWS) uses multiply scattered sound, described by the diffusi on approximation, to measure the relative motion of scatterers. This thesis explains the underlying principles governing these techniques and the ways that these techniques can be implemented in practice to provide powerful new methods for investigating th e dynamics of strongly scattering materials. I also take advantage of the ability of ultrasonic detectors to detect the wave field directly to test the Siegert relation. The Siegert relation is a simple relationship between the field and intensity temporal autocorrelation functions, and is frequently used in the interpretation of analogous light scattering techniques. I have elucidated the conditions under which the Siegert relation is obeyed through a systematic study of this basic wave relation for both single and multiple scattering. W e also take advantage of our ability to measure the phase of the scattered waves, and sh ow how the statistics underlying their temporal fluctuations can be used to investigate the scatterer's dynamics. Using DAWS and DSS, I have investigated the dynamics of particles suspend ed against sedimentation by a fluid flowing upwards in a fluidized bed. Since ultrasonic wavelengths are on the order of millimeters, the suspensions that can be probed contain particles with diameters on the millimeter scale; this corresponds to a regi me that is of interest in industrial applications. Thus DAWS and DSS are well suited to th e high Reynolds number, high volume fraction suspensions to which other current techniques are least suited. In our experiments, the velocity fluctuations and velocity correlation lengths 302 are measured as a function of the volume fraction and sample size for a rang e of Reynolds numbers. At high volume fractions of particles (~ > 0.15), we find surprisingly large values of the rms velocity fluctuations and instantaneous correlation length , with a different dependence on volume fraction to that seen at low ~. The relationship between the velocity and correlation length is explained for all volume fractions by accounting for the fundamental importance of number fluctuations in setting the scale of th e dynamics. column12: Deformation-control system and method
column13: A system for selectively controlling deformation. The system includes a first mechanism for resisting deformation about an axis of an accompanying fluid foil. A second mechanism, in communication with the first mechanism, enables deformation along the axis and/or at an angle to the axis. In more a specific embodiment, the axis is a lengthwise axis of the fluid foil, which is a transformable airfoil, and the system includes a bellows device that is approximately concentric with the axis. The bellows device is supported by first base structure at one end and a second base structure at another end. The deformation at an angle to the first axis includes shear deformation or bending deformation. The deformation along the axis includes extension or strain deformation. The deformation about the axis includes torsion deformation.

Ο εμβολέας περιλαμβάνει ένα τοίχωμα που έχει μία εσωτερική επιφάνεια και ένα ή περισσότερα προς τα έσω προεξέχοντα παρεμβύσματα τοποθετημένα στην εσωτερική επιφάνεια του τοιχώματος. Κατά προτίμηση, η εσωτερική επιφάνεια του τοιχώματος ορίζει ένα υποστήριγμα συγκράτησης που σχηματίζεται κατά μήκος ενός αξονικού επιπέδου αυτού και τα προς τα έσω προεξέχοντα παρεμβύσματα απέχουν μεταξύ τους ακτινικά κατά μήκος της εσωτερικής επιφάνειας του τοιχώματος και εκτείνονται σε μία διαμήκη κατεύθυνση πλησίον του υποστηρίγματος συγκράτησης. Η σύριγγα μπορεί να χρησιμοποιηθεί με έναν εγχυτήρα που συμπεριλαμβάνει ένα μέλος μετάδοσης κίνησης. Το μέλος μετάδοσης κίνησης κατά προτίμηση περιλαμβάνει τουλάχιστον ένα μέλος συγκράτησης προσαρμοσμένο να συμπλέκει το υποστήριγμα συγκράτησης του εμβολέα της σύριγγας ώστε να επιτρέπεται στο μέλος μετάδοσης της κίνησης να ανασύρει τον εμβολέα με το σώμα της σύριγγας. Περαιτέρω, το μέλος μετάδοσης κίνησης κατά προτίμηση περιλαμβάνει ένα ή περισσότερα προς τα έξω εκτεινόμενα μέλη παρεμβύσματος προσαρμοσμένα να συμπλέκονται από τα προς τα έσω προεξέχοντα παρεμβύσματα των εμβολέων της σύριγγας. Τα προς τα έξω εκτεινόμενα μέλη του παρεμβύσματος είναι λειτουργικά συνδεδεμένα με το τουλάχιστον ένα μέλος συγκράτησης έτσι ώστε όταν το σώμα της σύριγγας περιστρέφεται και τα προς τα έσω προεξέχοντα παρεμβύσματα στον εμβολέα να συμπλέκονται και να μετακινούν τα προς τα έξω εκτεινόμενα μέλη του παρεμβύσματος στο μέλος μετάδοσης κίνησης, όπου το τουλάχιστον ένα μέλος συγκράτησης στο μέλος μετάδοσης κίνησης ανασύρεται και αποσυμπλέκεται από το υποστήριγμα συγκράτησης του εμβολέα της σύριγγας.

column12: Fluid layer acoustic shield for turbofan jet propulsion engine
column13: Noise generated by the tips of the fan blades in a turbofan jet propulsion engine is suppressed by generating an annular fluid layer or wake in the inlet of the turbofan engine forwardly from the fan blades and spaced inwardly from the inner wall of the inlet and by lining the inner wall of the inlet with an acoustically absorbent layer of material. Sound waves generated by the fan blades are reflected outwardly by the fluid layer and are absorbed in the acoustic absorbent layer on the inner wall of the inlet. In order for the wake to reflect sound waves, either the local fluid velocity in the wake must be lower than the fluid velocity of the surrounding airstream traveling through the inlet or the acoustic speed in the wake must be greater than or equal to the acoustic speed in the surrounding airstream. It is preferred that both conditions be met. The fluid layer can be created by an annular bluff body positioned in the inlet or by injecting a fluid from an annular plenum in a direction opposite to the flow of the airstream through the inlet.

column12: ROBOTIC POWERED CARGO HANDLING SYSTEM
column13: An exemplary embodiment may provide a robotic powered cargo handling system. An embodiment may implement a pallet-lift mechanism to lift cargo or pallets. Powered rollers may be embedded into the forks of a pallet-lift mechanism and on top of the vehicle body. An exemplary embodiment may be fully autonomous. A user or software may direct the vehicle to a pallet or piece of cargo and set a destination for the cargo. Sensors, cameras, GPS, and computer vision may be implemented to navigate and avoid obstacles. An exemplary embodiment may include independent 4-wheel steering, 4 corner height adjustment, in-hub electric motors, and pneumatic or solid tires.

column12: Sintered, aluminous abrasive
column13: Aluminous abrasive bodies are prepared by wet grinding pure alumina with selected sintering agents to a particle size of less than 5 microns, drying the ground slip to a moisture content of not more than 10%, sieving and compacting at a pressure of up to 5 tons p.s.i., granulating to the required grain size and sintering at 1350-1550 DEG C. for up to two hours. The surplus fines from the granulating stage may be incorporated into the ground slip either prior to, or after drying. Alternatively, the pressed compact may be pre-sintered at 500-1400 DEG C., crushed to a particle size of 0.1-1.0 mm., and incorporated into the ground slip as above. The sintering agents, which are silica, titania, magnesia, calcia, iron oxides, manganese oxides, cuprous oxide and sodium oxide, may be incorporated as such or in combination as clays, red mud or ilmenite for example up to a maximum of 20%.

column12: LOCKING SPINAL FUSION DEVICE
column13: A spinal fusion device for implantation between spinal vertebrae includes an implant member having an opposed upper and lower surface, an outer sidewall having an aperture having internal threads, and an inner sidewall defining a central opening. A plate member is attached to the implant member such that the plate member is perpendicular relative to the implant member and includes a plurality of angled apertures for receiving anchoring fasteners and a central aperture for receiving a locking fastener. A locking member is attached to the cage member. The locking member includes a tubular shaft having internal threads that is inserted through the aperture of the outer sidewall of the implant member. A locking fastener is inserted through the central aperture of the plate member and into the locking member to thereby lock the spinal fusion device in position.

column12: SWAB DISPENSER
column13: A swab dispenser system is provided that includes a reusable outer receptacle and a replaceable refill container insertable therewithin. The outer receptacle is formed with a fin projecting vertically upwardly and centrally positioned on the bottom panel of the receptacle. The fin has a horizontal length greater than a width thereof. The refill container on its bottom wall also includes a fin. The fin of the refill container has a hollow interior for form-fittingly receiving the fin projecting upwardly from the receptacle bottom panel. Function of the fin is to allow a consumer to properly orient the refill container when placing same into the receptacle. The fin also functions to direct swabs into a proper arrangement when they are being factory filled into the container. Furthermore, the position and geometry of the fin maximizes the number of swabs fillable into the container. Figure 3.

column12: A carrier/solvent system comprising an amine hydrochloride, phosphorous acid & optionally phosphoric acid
column13: A carrier/solvent system comprises an amine hydrochloride, phosphorous acid and optionally phosphoric acid, wherein the phosphorous acid and optional phosphoric acid may be produced in situ (eg by the reaction of water with phosphorous chloride and phosphorous oxychloride respectively). The amine hydrochloride is preferably the hydrochloride of a C<SB>1-8</SB> primary, secondary or tertiary amine, especially of trimethylamine, triethylamine, tripropylamine or tributylamine. This system may be used as the carrier/solvent in the preparation of a bisphosphonate by the reaction of a carbonyl compound with a phosphorus halide (especially a phosphorous trihalide such as the trichloride or tribromide).

column12: LOCKING SPINAL FUSION DEVICE
column13: A spinal fusion device for implantation between spinal vertebrae includes an implant member having an opposed upper and lower surface, an outer sidewall having an aperture having internal threads, and an inner sidewall defining a central opening. A plate member is attached to the implant member such that the plate member is perpendicular relative to the implant member and includes a plurality of angled apertures for receiving anchoring fasteners and a central aperture for receiving a locking fastener. A locking member is attached to the cage member. The locking member includes a tubular shaft having internal threads that is inserted through the aperture of the outer sidewall of the implant member. A locking fastener is inserted through the central aperture of the plate member and into the locking member to thereby lock the spinal fusion device in position.

column12: Method and system for determining computer resource usage in utility computing
column13: A universal platform for utility computing that allows service providers to charge clients for the services rendered according to a dimensionless cross-platform universal metric. The platform measures or monitors six metrics commonly used in software computing (MHz for CPU usage, Mbytes for memory usage, Kbytes/sec for I/O, Kbytes/sec for LAN, Kbits/sec for WAN and Gbytes for storage) and applies appropriate weighting and conversion factors to each consumption value to a value in the universal metric that can be applied agnostically to any system or application. The metric can also take other controllable variables into account, such as real estate cost, tax jurisdiction and electrical power. The metric effectively a metric makes diverse computing resources comparable. The total value of the resources consumed by a user determines the cost charged for the use of the computing services.

column12: Swab dispenser
column13: A swab dispenser system is provided that includes a reusable outer receptacle and a replaceable refill container insertable therewithin. The outer receptacle is formed with a fin projecting vertically upwardly and centrally positioned on the bottom panel of the receptacle. The fin has a horizontal length greater than a width thereof. The refill container on its bottom wall also includes a fin. The fin of the refill container has a hollow interior for form-fittingly receiving the fin projecting upwardly from the receptacle bottom panel. Function of the fin is to allow a consumer to properly orient the refill container when placing same into the receptacle. The fin also functions to direct swabs into a proper arrangement when they are being factory filled into the container. Furthermore, the position and geometry of the fin maximizes the number of swabs fillable into the container.

column12: Tıbbı enjektörlerle birlikte kullanılmaya yönelik şırıngalar, şırınga arayüzleri ve şırınga pistonları.
column13: Bir şırınga, bir gövde ve gövde içinde hareketli bir şekilde yerleştirilmiş bir piston içerir. Piston bir iç yüzeye sahip bir duvar ve duvarın iç yüzeyine yerleştirilmiş bir veya daha fazla içeri doğru çıkıntı yapan flanş içerir. Tercihen, duvarın iç yüzeyi, bunun eksenel bir düzlemi boyunca oluşturulan bir tutma tırnağını tanımlar ve içeri doğru çıkıntı yapan flanşlar, duvarın iç yüzeyi boyunca radyal olarak yerleştirilir ve tutma tırnağına yakın olan uzunlamasına bir doğrultuda uzanır. Şırınga, bir tahrik elemanı içeren bir enjektör ile birlikte kullanılabilir. Tahrik elemanı tercihen tahrik elemanının pistonu şırınga gövdesiyle geri çekmesine izin vermek için şırınga pistonunun tutma tırnağına bağlanmak üzere uyarlanmış en az bir tespit elemanı içerir. Ayrıca, tahrik elemanı tercihen, şırınga pistonlarının içten çıkıntı yapan flanşları tarafından bağlanmış şekilde uyarlanmış bir veya daha fazla dışa doğru uzanan flanş elemanlarını içerir. Dışa doğru uzanan flanş elemanları, en az bir tespit elemanına işlevsel bir şekilde bağlanır, şöyle ki, şırınga gövdesi döndürüldüğünde ve piston üzerindeki içe doğru çıkıntı yapan flanşlar tahrik elemanı üzerinde dışa doğru uzanan flanş elemanlarına bağlandığında ve hareket ettiğinde, tahrik elemanı üzerindeki en az bir tespit elemanı geri çekilir ve şırınga pistonunun tutucu tırnağından ayrılır.

column12: Idle measurement periods in a communication network
column13: A transmission frame is communicated to cause a media idle measurement period on a contention based communication media. The media idle measurement period (i.e., “quiet period”) provides a period of inactivity on the communications medium that may be used to detect for the presence of foreign signals such as radio broadcast interference, noise, or other signals, or may be used for calibration of circuitry coupled to the communications medium. Idle measurement periods may be caused regularly (e.g., periodically). The transmission frame may include an explicit instruction for the media idle measurement period or may cause the media idle measurement period by simulating a collision on the communications media.

If the terminal (  34  ) is hot, current will pass from the shunt (  20  ) to a relay coil (  62  ) to close contacts (  64  ) in a Form C relay (  60  ). When the normally open switch contacts (  64  ) are closed a bypass circuit (  52  ) disconnects the terminals (  14, 34  ) in the connectors (  10, 30  ) so arcing will not occur when the connectors (  10, 30  ) are mated or unmated under load. column12: TELECOMMUNICATIONS ARRANGEMENTS AND METHODS
column13: Cellular telephone networks (I, II, III and IV) (e.g. GSM networks) are respectively situated within different geographical regions. Instead, the networks have concluded service agreements with an international roaming platform (IRP 30). When a subscriber (MS 20III) of one of these other networks (III) is roaming in a visited network (I), a registration request is passed by the MSC (12A) of the visited network (I) to the international roaming platform (IRP 30) which checks that the visited network (I) and the home network (III) of the subscriber (MS 20III) have concluded service agreements with it and then passes the request to the home location register (HLR 10) of the home network (III). The calls themselves are not routed via the international roaming platform (IRP 30).

column12: IDLE MEASUREMENT PERIODS IN A COMMUNICATION NETWORK
column13: A transmission frame is communicated to cause a media idle measurement period on a contention based communication media. The media idle measurement period (i.e., quiet period) provides a period of inactivity on the communications medium that may be used to detect for the presence of foreign signals such as radio broadcast interference, noise, or other signals, or may be used for calibration of circuitry coupled to the communications medium. Idle measurement periods may be caused regularly (e.g., periodically). The transmission frame may include an explicit instruction for the media idle measurement period or may cause the media idle measurement period by simulating a collision on the communications media.

column12: Double barrier system for an in situ conversion process
column13: A heating system for a subsurface formation is described. The heating system includes a first heater, a second heater, and a third heater placed in an opening in the subsurface formation. Each heater includes: an electrical conductor; an insulation layer at least partially surrounding the electrical conductor; and an electrically conductive sheath at least partially surrounding the insulation layer. The electrical conductor is electrically coupled to the sheath at a lower end portion of the heater. The lower end portion is the portion of the heater distal from a surface of the opening. The first heater, the second heater, and the third heater are electrically coupled at the lower end portions of the heaters. The first heater, the second heater, and the third heater are configured to be electrically coupled in a three-phase wye configuration.

column12: Method of Interconnecting Communication Networks
column13: Networks III and IV have concluded service agreements with an international roaming platform (IRP 30) rather than bilaterally with networks I and III. When a subscriber (MS 20111) of one of these networks (III) is roaming in a visited network (I), a registration request is passed by the MSC (12A) of the visited network (I) to the international roaming platform (IRP 30) which checks that the visited network (I) and the home network (III) of the subscriber (MS 20III) have concluded service agreements with it and then passes the request to the home location register (HLR 10) of the home network (III). This home location register then produces authentication data which is transmitted by the international roaming platform (IRP 30) to the visited network (I) for authenticating the visiting subscriber (MS 20111). The subscriber's details are temporarily stored in the VLR (14A) of the visited network (I) and the subscriber's location is stored in the HLR (10) of the home network (III), thereby enabling the calls to be routed to and from the visiting subscriber (MS 20111). The calls themselves are not routed via the international roaming platform (IRP 30).

column12: Manual multiple size can crusher
column13: A manual can crusher for crushing a can having a housing with a top opening for receiving a can to be crushed, a bottom opening for discharging a crushed can, and an interior crushing wall with a creasing block mounted thereon. A crushing ram is disposed within the housing and is pivotable between an open position where the ram is opposite the crushing wall and a closed position where the ram is adjacent to the crushing wall. A longitudinally extending handle is rotatably mounted on the housing, and linkage couples the handle to the ram. A can to be crushed is placed into the top opening and the handle is rotated to move the ram between the open and closed positions via the linkage. The can is crushed against the interior crushing wall until is is sufficiently crushed to be discharged through the bottom opening.

column12: Production of phthalic anhydride
column13: Phthalic anhydride is produced by the vapour phase partial oxidation of a hydrocarbon precursor, and the mixture produced is quenched with a methyl naphthalene to give a slurry of the anhydride in methyl naphthalene, from which the anhydride is recovered. The hydrocarbon precursor may be o-xylene, naphthalene or methyl naphthalene. The quench medium separated from the anhydride may be recirculated to form part of the feed mixture to be oxidized. The off gases from the quench treatment are scrubbed with water to recover maleic acid, maleic anhydride and fumaric acid.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR REDUCING HUMAN VERTEBRAL BODY SUBSIDENCE USING VARIABLE SURFACE AREA INTERBODY CAGES CORRELATED TO LOCALIZED BONE DENSITY MEASUREMENTS
column13: An improved interbody spinal implant which takes into account specific patient variables. During the preoperative phase an interactive CT radiodensity scan of localized portions of the vertebrae is used to determine whether the template for a preselected implant will minimize subsidence based on the Hounsfield Unit score and a corresponding calculated Hounsfield Parameter value generated by the scan for the contact surface area of the selected implant. If not, a template for another selected implant having different medial and lateral dimensions is selected and placed over the interactive CT scan. If acceptable Hounsfield Parameters are generated this means acceptable minimal subsidence will occur. The surgeon may then evaluate the size of the bone graft window or the implant opening permitting the surface contact area of the implant with the superior and inferior vertebrae to determine if it is acceptable to ensure proper fusion and minimize subsidence.

column13: CONJUNTO DE MISTURA DE FLUIDOS. A presente invenção refere-se a um dispositivo de mistura de fluidos para misturar um primeiro fluido de injeção e um segundo fluido de injeção que inclui uma primeira entrada de fluido, uma segunda entrada de fluido, uma câmara de mistura em comunicação de fluido com a primeira e segunda entradas de fluido, e uma porta de saída em comunicação de fluido com a câmara de mistura. A primeira entrada de fluido está configurada para conduzir o primeiro fluido de injeção em uma primeira direção e tem uma primeira superfície de redirecionamento. A segunda entrada de fluido está configurada para conduzir o segundo fluido de injeção em uma segunda direção ao longo de um eixo geométrico diferente da primeira direção e tem uma segunda superfície de redirecionamento. A câmara de mistura está configurada para misturar o primeiro fluido de injeção e o segundo fluido juntos. A mistura do primeiro fluido de injeção e do segundo fluido de injeção sai do dispositivo de mistura de fluidos através da porta de saída.

column12: Electrical connector with shunt for hot mating and unmating
column13: A connector assembly ( 2 ) includes and arc prevention shunt ( 20 ) in one of two mating electrical connectors ( 10, 30 ). If the terminal ( 34 ) is hot, current will pass from the shunt ( 20 ) to a relay coil ( 62 ) to close contacts ( 64 ) in a Form C relay ( 60 ). When the normally open switch contacts ( 64 ) are closed a bypass circuit ( 52 ) disconnects the terminals ( 14, 34 ) in the connectors ( 10, 30 ) so arcing will not occur when the connectors ( 10, 30 ) are mated or unmated under load. column13: An oriented heat-sealable antistatic polypropylene film is manufactured by applying to one or both surfaces of a base polypropylene film, preferably by co-extrusion, a layer of a heat-sealable olefinic polymer (for example, a predominantly linear random copolymer of ethylene with butene-1) containing between 0.2 and 10% by weight of an anionic hydrocarbyl (preferably long chain alkyl) sulphonate. column12: DIGITAL MULTIPLIER
column13: The digital CMOS/LSI synchronous serial multiplier includes a register to store an X-bit sign magnitude multiplier in parallel. (X - 1) adder stages are connected in series. A control arrangement coupled to the register, the multiplicand input and the adder stages are provided to couple each of the magnitude bits of the multiplier number into a different one of the adder stages with the adder stages performing successive additions of the magnitude bits of the multiplier number to provide as an output of a last of the adder stages a serial product having M bits. column12: Shunt
column13: A shunt for draining cerebral spinal fluid from the brain is provided. In an embodiment, the shunt includes a master control unit that is located in the abdomen, which interconnects a ventricular catheter and a second catheter, typically located in the peritoneal cavity. In a specific embodiment, the master control unit includes a variety of smart features including at least one access port to allow the injection of solutions for the prevention or removal of blockages in the catheter, and/or antibiotics. The access port can have other uses, such as allowing a point of access for physical navigation of a catheter or the like within the shunt, thereby providing another option for breaking-up blockages, and/or allowing an access point for repairing the shunt's components. Additionally, the master control unit includes a diagnostic unit that transmits, either wirelessly or through a wired connection via the access port, diagnostic information about the status of the patient and/or the shunt.

column12: Solvent pulping process
column13: Solvent pulping of wood chips or other fibrous plant material is effected using an aqueous solution of a lower aliphatic alcohol in a plurality of batch extraction vessels. The charge in each vessel is heated rapidly to pulping temperature by recirculation of a primary extraction liquor having a relatively high dissolved solids content, and thereafter the charge is subjected to a series of once-through extractions or washes with successively cleaner liquors, including a final extraction or wash with fresh liquor. The extraction liquor from one extraction stage in one vessel is used in another extraction stage in another vessel. Upon completion of the extraction, the liquor is drained from the vessel, the vessel is depressurized to a solvent condenser, and the remaining solvent is steam stripped from the charge and recovered. The used extraction liquor is treated in an alcohol recovery system by flash vaporization, condensation of the solvent vapors, and vacuum stripping of the residual liquor with steam. The alcohol-free extract is then treated to recover a concentrated aqueous lignin suspension and a concentrated aqueous carbohydrate solution.

column12: Compact television antenna system
column13: A highly compact and lightweight 82 channel all banded VHF-UHF television antenna having three antenna elements wherein each element is the identical physical length and each element includes two half sections. Each antenna element is separated a predetermined distance from each other element wherein the predetermined distance is substantially less than one-tenth of the shortest wave length in the VHF band. A first set of coils are utilized to electrically lengthen the halves of the two elements for reception in the VHF band and a second set of coils are utilized to provide proper delays between the signals received by each antenna element so that when the signals are combined the signals are substantially additive and in phase. The antenna system includes a weatherproof housing containing a rotor, a preamplifier, and electronic circuitry. A deloading mechanism is arranged around the housing to engage the circumference of each antenna element to provide stability under the driving forces that may occur in the atmosphere.

column12: ELECTRICAL CONNECTOR WITH SHUNT FOR HOT MATING AND UNMATING
column13: A connector assembly (2) includes and arc prevention shunt (20) in one of tw o mating electrical connectors (10, 30). The shunt (20) engages a terminal (34 ) when the connectors (10) and (20) are in a partially mated configuration. If the terminal (34) is hot, current will pass from the shunt (20) to a relay coil (62) to close contacts (64) in a Form C relay (60). When the normally open switch contacts (64) are closed a bypass circuit (52) disconnects the terminals (14, 34) in the connectors (10, 30) so arcing will not occur when the connectors (10, 30) are mated or unmated unde r load. When the connectors (10, 30) are in the fully mated or fully unmated, the shunt (20) is electrically isolated from the terminals (14, 34).

column12: Digital vocoder
column13: This invention relates to a digital vocoder where speech is translated to a digital version thereof. An adaptive filter in the form of an N stage Itakura type cascade derives from the speech a prediction residual and N spectral parameter in the form of weighting coefficients of the filter. The pitch period, derived from the prediction residual, the voiced/unvoiced decision derived from the first of the weighting coefficients and the peak amplitude of a pitch pulse, and a digital signal representing filter gain, derived from the last of the weighting coefficients are multiplexed with each other and the N spectral parameters for transmission to a receiver. The receiver employs an excitation generator responsive to the pitch period, the gain signal and the voiced/unvoiced decision to produce an excitation signal to excite an N/2 cascade connected stage receive filter. Each stage of the receive filter operates on a time shared basis on an adjacent pair of the N spectral parameters. The receive adaptive filter operation is the inverse of the transmit adaptive filter so that after digital to analog conversion the original speech is substantially reproduced.
column15: DUNN JAMES GRANT;;COWAN JOHN RICHARD;;RUSSO ANTHONY JOSEPH

column12: Reactivation of hydrocarbon isomerization catalysts
column13: In a process for isomerizing C.sub.4 -C.sub.7 alkanes and/or C.sub.6 -C.sub.7 cycloalkanes which is carried out in the presence of hydrogen gas, a chloride additive (e.g., CCl.sub.4 or C.sub.2 Cl.sub.4) and a supported platinum and chlorine-containing catalyst (e.g., Pt/Cl/Al.sub.2 O.sub.3), the catalyst is intermittently reactivated in two steps: first, the hydrogen to feed hydrocarbon ratio is raised (while the chloride level in the feed is either not changed or lowered), and thereafter the chloride level in the feed is increased. Preferably, the fresh catalyst is also preactivated by contacting it with the hydrocarbon feed wherein the hydrogen to feed hydrocarbon ratio is higher and/or the temperature is lower than what is employed in the subsequent isomerization production cycle.

column12: Systems, methods, and devices for analyzing utility usage with load duration curves
column13: Systems, methods, and devices for regulating usage of at least one utility by a utility consuming system. One aspect of the present disclosure is directed to a method for regulating usage of at least one utility by a utility consuming system having a plurality of utility consuming segments. The method includes: generating a load duration curve (LDC); selecting a portion of the LDC to be analyzed; generating an associated duration chart (ADC) that is indicative of one or more associated duration parameters relating to the selected portion of the LDC; and modifying usage of the utility by at least one of the utility consuming segments based, at least in part, upon the one or more associated duration parameters indicated in the first ADC.

column12: SHUNT
column13: A shunt for draining cerebral spinal fluid from the brain is provided. In an embodiment, the shunt includes a master control unit that is located in the abdomen, which interconnects a ventricular catheter and a second catheter, typically located in the peritoneal cavity. In a specific embodiment, the master control unit includes a variety of 'smart' features including at least one access port to allow the injection of solutions for the prevention or removal of blockages in the catheter, and/or antibiotics. The access port can have other uses, such as allowing a point o f access for physical navigation of a catheter or the like within the shunt, thereby providing another option for breaking-up blockages, and/or allowing an access point fo r repairing the shunt's components. Additionally, the master control unit includes a diagnostic unit that transmits, either wirelessly or through a wired connection via the access port, diagnostic information about the status of the patient and/or t he shunt.

column12: Method and apparatus for determining the size distribution of tobacco
column13: Tobacco is graded by size by separating a sample into size fractions using a rotary drum screen. The sample is characterized by two distribution curves, one for a finer portion and the other for a coarser portion. The crossing point of logarithmic plots of the percentage by weight vs. particle size distributions of the two portions provides a precise and sensitive descriptor, which can be termed as a "percent desirable fraction," for grading the size characteristics of threshed or cut tobacco.
